1. Install homebrew:
/usr/bin/ruby -e "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/master/install)”

2. Install graphviz:
brew install graphviz

3. Alias the dot command:
alias doit="/usr/local/bin/dot -T png -O"

4. Create a simple graphviz document:
Cat > test.dot

graph { 
		a -- b; 
		b -- c; 
		a -- c; 
		d -- c; 
		e -- c; 
		e -- a; 
	} 

Ctrl-d

5. Create the png of the graph:
doit test.dot


Now, for more automation:
$ cat alwaysdoit.sh
#!/bin/bash

IMAGETYPE=png

if [[ -e $1 ]]; then
  echo looking for $1
  while ((1)); do
    if [ "$1" -nt "${1}.${IMAGETYPE}" ]; then
      echo "updating image"
      /usr/bin/dot -T $IMAGETYPE -O $1
    fi
    sleep 1
  done
else
  echo Usage: $0 file.dot
  echo The monitored file must exist
fi;

The script might generate the file twice because of timing issues, but who cares…

$ bash alwaysdoit.sh test.dot
